prompt:
Implement PR-C of the user-equipment-inventory feature for Flux: the planner integration that filters the catalog by the user's inventory before sending it to the LLM, and validates the generated program against inventory on the way back.

PR-A added the equipment catalog at src/data/equipmentCatalog.ts and equipmentRequired/equipmentAlternatives on Exercise. PR-B added the inventory store (LocationsState wrapped per src/data/inventory.ts), Settings UI, and constrained weight picker in ExerciseCard. Build on both.

Note: the LLM provider in src/llm/index.ts is a stub today — the only provider is NOT_CONFIGURED which throws 'LLM not configured'. This is expected. PR-C's job is to make the orchestration callable; actual BYOK / local providers land in a later PR per the umbrella plan. The orchestrator must work end-to-end against a mocked provider in tests and degrade gracefully in the UI when activeProvider.available is false.

## Scope

### 1. New src/llm/programGen.ts — orchestrator

The single entry point for AI program generation.

```ts
import type { Exercise } from '../data/types';
import type { Inventory } from '../data/inventory';
import type { Program } from '../tabs/Workouts/types';
import type { Finding } from '../db/programSchema';

export interface FilteredExercise {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  muscleGroups: string[];
  equipmentRequired: string[];
  // Resolved against inventory. null = bodyweight / no weight. [] never
  // appears here because unsupported exercises are dropped upstream.
  allowedWeights: number[] | null;
  // Pass-through cues the planner uses for context.
  techniqueNote?: string;
  demoVideoId?: string;
}

export interface FilteredCatalog {
  exercises: FilteredExercise[];
  // Counts for telemetry / UI ('We filtered the catalog from 16 to 11
  // exercises based on your inventory').
  totalCatalogSize: number;
  supportedCount: number;
}

// Build the catalog the planner sees: only exercises the user can perform
// with their current inventory, annotated with allowed weights per exercise.
export function buildFilteredCatalog(inv: Inventory): FilteredCatalog;

export interface ProgramGenerationResult {
  program: Program;
  warnings: Finding[];           // from validateProgramSchema with inventory
  filteredCatalog: FilteredCatalog;
}

export interface GenerateProgramOptions {
  inventory: Inventory;
  // Free-form natural-language request from the user — phase intent, goals,
  // duration, previous-phase summary, etc. Mirrors what prompts/generate-phase.md
  // already collects manually.
  userRequest: string;
  // Optional: the previous phase's program for adaptation context.
  previousProgram?: Program;
}

// Orchestrates: build filtered catalog → render prompt → call generate() →
// parse → validate → return.
//
// Throws when activeProvider is NOT_CONFIGURED (so UI can show 'configure in
// Settings'). Throws on JSON-parse failures or hard schema errors. Returns
// warnings (not errors) when the program is structurally valid but violates
// inventory constraints — UI shows these for user review.
export async function generateProgram(opts: GenerateProgramOptions): Promise<ProgramGenerationResult>;
```

buildFilteredCatalog implementation:
- Iterate EXERCISE_CATALOG entries.
- For each: use isExerciseSupportedByInventory(ex, inv) from PR-B's src/tabs/Workouts/logic/equipmentResolve.ts. Drop unsupported entries entirely.
- For supported entries with usesWeight: call allowedWeightsForExercise(ex, inv). Use null when usesWeight=false.
- Preserve totalCatalogSize and supportedCount in the result.

generateProgram implementation:
- Build filtered catalog.
- Render the prompt template (see step 2 — this PR also writes the runtime template). The prompt MUST include:
  - The full filtered catalog as a JSON block (id, name, muscleGroups, equipmentRequired, allowedWeights, techniqueNote)
  - The user's natural-language request
  - The output schema (re-use the JSON schema spec from prompts/generate-phase.md, but constrain exercise_id to enum of filtered ids and starting_weight to 'must be in the allowed_weights list for the chosen exercise')
- Call generate({ prompt, schema: PROGRAM_SCHEMA }) from src/llm/index.ts. Single Promise<string>, not streaming (streaming is a future enhancement).
- Parse JSON.parse the response. Wrap parse errors in a clear 'AI returned non-JSON' error.
- Run validateProgramSchema(program, EXERCISE_CATALOG, inventory) from src/db/programSchema.ts (extended in PR-A with the warnings channel). If errors.length > 0, throw with the first few errors in the message — the program is unusable. Warnings flow back unchanged.
- Return { program, warnings, filteredCatalog }.

### 2. Update prompts/generate-phase.md

The current file is a manual paste-into-an-AI template. Two changes:

(a) Add a clearly-marked 'RUNTIME PROMPT TEMPLATE' section at the top that programGen.ts embeds and substitutes. Use moustache-style {{placeholders}} for substitution by the orchestrator:

```
{{user_request}}

You are generating a workout program for Flux. Pick exercises ONLY from
the filtered catalog below. Every exercise_id in your output must appear
in this list. For exercises with allowed_weights, starting_weight MUST be
a value from that list (or omitted entirely).

## Filtered exercise catalog

{{filtered_catalog_json}}

## Previous program (for adaptation context)

{{previous_program_or_none}}

## Output schema

Output a single valid JSON object: { meta, phases: [{ id, name, duration_weeks, description?, schedule_pattern?, workouts: { [key]: { name, focus, exercises: [{ exercise_id, sets, reps, rest, starting_weight?, weight_increment? }] } } }] }.

meta.principles must include: injury_prevention, mobility_every_phase, form_over_load, longevity_focus. meta.constraints must include { mobility_required: true, min_mobility_days_per_week: 1 }.

Output ONLY the JSON object, no commentary.
```

(b) Keep the existing manual prompt content below the runtime template, behind a divider, as the 'manual fallback' for users who don't have an LLM provider configured. Mark it clearly: 'Until an LLM provider is configured in Settings, use the manual template below — copy your equipment list, profile, and previous-phase data into the prompt and paste into an external AI.'

The runtime template lives in this same file so the manual and runtime versions stay in sync.

programGen.ts reads this file via Vite's `?raw` import:

```ts
